snippet.textDisplay:
i hav been listening to this song since its release and i must say I was so happy to see Indians liking Pakistani Coke Studio more and passing such wonderful sweet comments and thats what forced me to comment as well esp for those who couldnt understand it.
First of all, it opens up with a fresh fruity floral vibe in the voice of SanamMarvi and with an amazing transition, she is joined by SZahoor who has his own unique n dominating voice. Its mystic/sufi lyrics in centuries old punjabi language and if you want to feel the sould of it it lies in
LAAGI BINA NAIN NA JAGEY KOI
which means when you start loving your God/lord the most, you cant sleep and instead keep wandering and searching for Him the whole night till the very dawn, so painstakingly. And you cant do it on your own, unless He chosses you for this after you earn it.
You will also hear him singing CHAL MELE NU CHALIYE. Now, mela is generally known as a festive gathering where there is fin for everyone. But in this song, mela means milan and milap, meeting and coming face to face with your beloved one, the lord.
I can interpret it all as I have studied the original versions of the Punjabi books such as Heer Waris Shah, Saif Mulook, Kalaam Bulley Shah and Alif Allah Chambey Di Booti etc.

snippet.textDisplay: By giving this old Sufi kalam a contemporary musical  interpretation , you are helping revive and widen interest in Sufi philosophy. I commend you for doing it by featuring Sanam Marvi with Saieen Zahoor. I have been very fond of Sanam Marvi for years, but this combination is intoxicating in the truest sense. Even otherwise, your musical creations are an absolute joy to imbibe any day.
